1. Three points define a circle

In Euclidean geometry, a fundamental fact is:

Any three points that are not on the same straight line determine exactly one circle.

So if you have three points A, B, C (not collinear), there is one and only one circumcircle passing through them.

The triangle formed by the three points sits inside that circle.

      A
     / \
    /   \
   B-----C

The circle passes through A, B, and C.

This is called the circumcircle of the triangle.

⸻

2. Why three works

Two points only determine a line segment.
There are infinitely many circles through two points.

Three points fix the geometry.

Mathematically, the circle is determined because:

A circle needs three parameters:

(x_center, y_center, radius)

Three points give exactly enough constraints to solve those.

⸻

3. The triangle–circle relationship

Every triangle automatically creates several geometric centers:

Center	Meaning
Circumcenter	center of circle through all vertices
Centroid	center of mass
Incenter	center of inscribed circle
Orthocenter	intersection of altitudes

For your observation, the important one is the circumcenter.

That’s the point where perpendicular bisectors meet.

⸻

4. What if the points are on one line?

If the three points lie on a single straight line, then no finite circle exists.

In that case the triangle collapses.

So the condition is:

three non-collinear points


⸻

5. Why triangles show up everywhere

Triangles are the simplest stable geometric structure.

Reasons:
	1.	Three points define a plane.
	2.	Triangles cannot deform without changing side lengths.
	3.	They are the smallest rigid polygon.

That’s why triangles appear in:
	•	engineering trusses
	•	computer graphics meshes
	•	navigation
	•	surveying
	•	physics simulations

